DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(84)90077-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387884900774
AB  - Agricultural mechanisation has been justified in the Sudan by reference to labour shortages. The International Labour Office (ILO) has recently cast doubt on this assumption and argued for a reduction in the pace of mechanisation. However the authors, using a microeconomic production function approach and cost-benefit analysis, suggest that the social return on imported agricultural machinery does still justify mechanisation. Furthermore, allowing for rationing in the market for capital goods, the choice of technique by Sudanese farmers is largely consistent with economic efficiency.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Structures of foreign trade and income distribution: The case of Mexico
AU  - Kim, Kwan S.
AU  - Turrubiate, Gerardo
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 16
IS  - 3
SP  - 263
EP  - 278
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/12/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(84)90078-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387884900786
AB  - Using Mexico's input-output tables and household survey data, this paper examines various trade strategies and their relationship to commodity production with a view to assesing their effect on the distribution of income. The model incorporates income-induced multiplier effects, taking into account the full range of input import-substitution possibilities. The results show that the differences in the impact on income, particularly, of the lower incomes, are most marked in the tensions between exportable and import-competing activities. On the whole, production per unit of output in the non-tradable sector produces as much factor income as that in the export sector. Expansion of exportable activities marginally improves the economic position of the poor in relation to other income groups, but only when direct effects are taken into account. If, however, domestic production meets the needs of intermediate imports, then the distribution of income remains unaffected by alternative trade strategies.
ER  - 

